The paper deals with a buffer management problem, which is a classic problem in computer science and falls under the category of data structures (cs.DS). The problem also involves information theory (cs.IT) as it deals with packets and their deadlines. The algorithm presented in the paper is randomized and involves analysis of its performance, which falls under the category of algorithms (cs.AL). The problem also has applications in networking (cs.NI) as it deals with managing packets in a network. Finally, the paper involves performance guarantees and optimization, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
